00:44:24.140 --> 00:44:27.890
was weird because I arrived
in Washington on Tuesday.

00:44:27.890 --> 00:44:30.050
And my first meeting
was cancelled.

00:44:30.050 --> 00:44:32.720
And the guy who was supposed to
chair my second was furloughed.

00:44:35.690 --> 00:44:39.180
But we did have furlough fries
for lunch, which was fun.

00:44:39.180 --> 00:44:41.530
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:41.530 --> 00:44:45.540
SIR LAWRENCE FREEDMAN: It's
actually a fascinating case

00:44:45.540 --> 00:44:50.662
because it appears
simply as sort

00:44:50.662 --> 00:44:54.810
of Congress versus the
Executive Branch or Republicans

00:44:54.810 --> 00:44:55.920
versus Democrats.

00:44:55.920 --> 00:44:58.550
But actually the
key question is why

00:44:58.550 --> 00:45:01.310
does a group of
Republican congressman

00:45:01.310 --> 00:45:05.660
feel able to withstand the
tremendous amount of pressure

00:45:05.660 --> 00:45:10.760
that in other circumstances
would be assumed to be almost

00:45:10.760 --> 00:45:13.640
irresistible
because it threatens

00:45:13.640 --> 00:45:19.480
the ability of your party to
win elections in the future?

00:45:19.480 --> 00:45:23.570
No opinion poll is suggesting
that the actions of the House

00:45:23.570 --> 00:45:27.150
Republicans at the moment are
anything other than unpopular,

00:45:27.150 --> 00:45:35.190
or that many of the
House Republicans

00:45:35.190 --> 00:45:36.160
are unhappy with this.

00:45:36.160 --> 00:45:39.800
But this is sufficient to tie
the hand of Speaker Boehner.

00:45:39.800 --> 00:45:42.285
So one question is why
doesn't he face them down?

00:45:42.285 --> 00:45:43.660
And that presumably
has something

00:45:43.660 --> 00:45:45.080
to do with his own position.

00:45:45.080 --> 00:45:48.300
But why do these
guys feel they don't

00:45:48.300 --> 00:45:49.840
have to worry about
this pressure?

00:45:49.840 --> 00:45:53.580
Because their own positions
are absolutely safe

00:45:53.580 --> 00:45:56.650
because of
redistricting, because

00:45:56.650 --> 00:46:01.940
of the fact that they can get
funds from wealthy supporters,

00:46:01.940 --> 00:46:03.760
and they don't have to
go through the party

00:46:03.760 --> 00:46:05.000
to get the funds.

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:07.050
They feel absolutely safe.

00:46:07.050 --> 00:46:11.780
And so they can pursue
this crusade, if you like,

00:46:11.780 --> 00:46:17.020
without personally having
to face the consequences.

00:46:17.020 --> 00:46:22.320
And it will have to be broken
when-- maybe they also think

00:46:22.320 --> 00:46:26.020
that because of the pressure
of default or something

00:46:26.020 --> 00:46:28.810
that the president will be the
one who has to blink first.

00:46:28.810 --> 00:46:30.390
Maybe that's also part of it.

00:46:30.390 --> 00:46:33.250
I don't see how he can't.

00:46:33.250 --> 00:46:35.811
So my guess is
that at some point

00:46:35.811 --> 00:46:38.060
there will be sufficient
pressure from the Republicans

00:46:38.060 --> 00:46:42.520
on Speaker Boehner that he
has to find some [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:42.520 --> 00:46:46.170
It's not immediately
obvious at the moment.

00:46:46.170 --> 00:46:49.200
And I think it's an absolutely
classic strategic problem

00:46:49.200 --> 00:46:53.410
because it's not just a
question of the tactics that

00:46:53.410 --> 00:46:54.170
are being adopted.

00:46:54.170 --> 00:46:57.180
It's the way the whole issue
is structured and also the way

00:46:57.180 --> 00:46:58.120
it's framed.

00:46:58.120 --> 00:47:02.070
So the speaker
wants it to appear

00:47:02.070 --> 00:47:04.695
as a problem with a
lack of compromise.

00:47:04.695 --> 00:47:08.660
The president wants it to
appear as a problem of extortion

00:47:08.660 --> 00:47:09.820
and bullying.

00:47:09.820 --> 00:47:12.610
It has very big consequences.

00:47:12.610 --> 00:47:16.000
The trouble with academic
students of strategy,

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:17.940
we can find all
sorts of grim events

00:47:17.940 --> 00:47:20.817
absolutely riveting
without thinking always

00:47:20.817 --> 00:47:21.650
of the consequences.

00:47:21.650 --> 00:47:25.050
I think it's very
serious because it

00:47:25.050 --> 00:47:26.990
goes to the heart
of the governability

00:47:26.990 --> 00:47:28.920
and the reputation
of the United States.

00:47:28.920 --> 00:47:31.390
But as a strategic
problem it reveals

00:47:31.390 --> 00:47:32.969
quite a lot of important issues.

00:47:32.969 --> 00:47:34.760
AUDIENCE: So your whole
talk really focused

00:47:34.760 --> 00:47:37.280
on the evolution of
strategy and then

00:47:37.280 --> 00:47:39.610
defining really
what is the success

00:47:39.610 --> 00:47:41.200
and what's the end goal.

00:47:41.200 --> 00:47:42.730
And I feel that
heavily in the path

00:47:42.730 --> 00:47:46.030
is this aspect of probability
and luck to actually get there.

00:47:46.030 --> 00:47:48.396
And over the years luck
has become probability,

00:47:48.396 --> 00:47:50.020
which now we have
predictive analytics.

00:47:50.020 --> 00:47:52.400
And I was wondering with
all the computing power

00:47:52.400 --> 00:47:54.051
and predictive
analytics these days,

00:47:54.051 --> 00:47:55.550
how much you felt
strategy was going

00:47:55.550 --> 00:47:56.925
to change in the
next five years,

00:47:56.925 --> 00:47:59.030
and what direction you
thought it would go?

00:47:59.030 --> 00:48:01.670
SIR LAWRENCE FREEDMAN:
That's really interesting.

00:48:01.670 --> 00:48:04.750
Clearly you can
trace this back--

00:48:04.750 --> 00:48:08.070
and I do trace it back-- to
the 1950s, and particularly

00:48:08.070 --> 00:48:14.580
the RAND Corporation,
which were the first to see

00:48:14.580 --> 00:48:19.980
the possibilities of making
calculations using computers,

00:48:19.980 --> 00:48:27.530
which they had, that the
human mind couldn't make

00:48:27.530 --> 00:48:30.460
and, in a sense,
simulating states

00:48:30.460 --> 00:48:32.800
of affairs that
would in other ways

00:48:32.800 --> 00:48:34.730
be beyond human imagination.

00:48:34.730 --> 00:48:42.845
So since then there's been
a continuing belief that it

00:48:42.845 --> 00:48:47.870
is actually possible to
crank in the variables,

00:48:47.870 --> 00:48:53.010
to almost experiment,
a little experiment

00:48:53.010 --> 00:48:55.190
in the way and engineer
would, and work out

00:48:55.190 --> 00:48:58.140
how things are likely work out.

00:48:58.140 --> 00:49:03.020
And I think if you're trying
to understand human behavior

00:49:03.020 --> 00:49:07.430
in the mass, a lot of basic
supply and demand stuff,

00:49:07.430 --> 00:49:08.950
this will stand
you in good stead.

00:49:08.950 --> 00:49:12.130
If you're talking about
relatively stable societies

00:49:12.130 --> 00:49:14.770
with growth and stable
behavior patterns,

00:49:14.770 --> 00:49:17.569
this could be quite interesting.

00:49:17.569 --> 00:49:19.110
But I wouldn't want
to be the one who

00:49:19.110 --> 00:49:23.850
relies upon it if it was
a really big decision.

00:49:23.850 --> 00:49:28.420
If it's an outlying
decision, if you're

00:49:28.420 --> 00:49:34.390
talking about situations
where the sample size is small

00:49:34.390 --> 00:49:39.900
and the variables are many and
the possibilities of chance

00:49:39.900 --> 00:49:42.920
and luck are considerable,
then as likely

00:49:42.920 --> 00:49:45.299
as not your predictions
will let you down.

00:49:45.299 --> 00:49:46.840
And you've always
got the possibility

00:49:46.840 --> 00:49:49.440
that somebody else is
doing the same calculations

00:49:49.440 --> 00:49:57.830
on the other side, and coming to
the same conclusions about what

00:49:57.830 --> 00:50:00.770
might happen, and
acting accordingly.

00:50:00.770 --> 00:50:02.980
There has been a degree
of experimentation.

00:50:02.980 --> 00:50:04.780
I mean, like all of
these experiments,

00:50:04.780 --> 00:50:07.030
they're largely done
on graduate students

00:50:07.030 --> 00:50:10.380
in this part of the world.

00:50:10.380 --> 00:50:13.180
So whether this is
representative behavior,

00:50:13.180 --> 00:50:13.740
one can ask.

00:50:13.740 --> 00:50:15.948
But they show actually that
people aren't necessarily

00:50:15.948 --> 00:50:16.830
naturally strategic.

00:50:16.830 --> 00:50:19.159
But they understand when
they're in these situations.

00:50:19.159 --> 00:50:21.200
They understand they need
to vary their behavior.

00:50:21.200 --> 00:50:25.460
If they're too predictable
in a sort of repeated game,

00:50:25.460 --> 00:50:26.790
they'll get caught up.

00:50:26.790 --> 00:50:30.440
So I think there
are possibilities

00:50:30.440 --> 00:50:36.470
to understand large areas
of human affairs, which

00:50:36.470 --> 00:50:38.930
often in many ways
are not political.

00:50:38.930 --> 00:50:41.500
They're just the way that
people operate and relate

00:50:41.500 --> 00:50:43.160
to their environment.

00:50:43.160 --> 00:50:46.170
But the more political it
becomes and the more conscious

00:50:46.170 --> 00:50:49.630
people are that
they're in a conflict,

00:50:49.630 --> 00:50:54.300
I think the less likely it
is that that will in the end

00:50:54.300 --> 00:50:56.657
take you as far as
people might hope.

00:50:56.657 --> 00:50:58.990
AUDIENCE: I was wondering if
you could talk a little bit

00:50:58.990 --> 00:51:02.330
about the roll of
process innovations,

00:51:02.330 --> 00:51:07.250
particularly things like
the Roman camp formation

00:51:07.250 --> 00:51:09.935
and John Boyd's
description of the OODA

00:51:09.935 --> 00:51:13.460
loop and the tactical
operation center

00:51:13.460 --> 00:51:18.540
and how they contribute
to changes in strategy.

00:51:18.540 --> 00:51:21.480
Oh, and also impact
as force multipliers.

00:51:21.480 --> 00:51:23.590
SIR LAWRENCE FREEDMAN: Yeah.

00:51:23.590 --> 00:51:25.752
I spent a bit of
time on John Boyd,

00:51:25.752 --> 00:51:27.460
more than the other
things you mentioned,

00:51:27.460 --> 00:51:32.860
because Boyd was an
innovative thinker.

00:51:32.860 --> 00:51:34.823
For those of you
who don't know, he

00:51:34.823 --> 00:51:42.120
was a fighter pilot who wrote
the manuals on dog fights out

00:51:42.120 --> 00:51:47.460
of this idea of the OODA
lopp, which is Observation,

00:51:47.460 --> 00:51:49.605
Orientation,
Decision, Adaptation.

00:51:49.605 --> 00:51:50.480
I think that's right.

00:51:53.290 --> 00:51:55.450
Which was a way of
getting to the idea

00:51:55.450 --> 00:51:59.850
that what was important was
thinking faster and more

00:51:59.850 --> 00:52:02.880
accurately than your opponent
rather than necessarily having

00:52:02.880 --> 00:52:04.175
more firepower.

00:52:04.175 --> 00:52:06.874
And it was a very
influential idea.

00:52:06.874 --> 00:52:07.790
It was not a bad idea.

00:52:07.790 --> 00:52:09.210
I mean, it had a lot of effect.

00:52:09.210 --> 00:52:13.765
And some of other of Boyd's
ideas were less successful.

00:52:20.720 --> 00:52:22.390
I don't think there's
any basic problem

00:52:22.390 --> 00:52:24.150
with the idea of the OODA loop.

00:52:24.150 --> 00:52:29.860
It's like one of these
things like SWAT analysis.

00:52:33.530 --> 00:52:36.490
They're useful tools once
you start thinking about it.

00:52:36.490 --> 00:52:39.180
What I thought you were going
to ask about when you started

00:52:39.180 --> 00:52:45.370
talking about process is
things where people have tried

00:52:45.370 --> 00:52:50.420
to change strategies that
have been based on essentially

00:52:50.420 --> 00:52:52.860
change the way you go
about your business,

00:52:52.860 --> 00:52:54.970
which a lot of business
strategies like that.

00:52:54.970 --> 00:52:56.969
And the one I spent a bit
of time on in the book

00:52:56.969 --> 00:53:00.060
is business process
re-engineering,

00:53:00.060 --> 00:53:06.810
which was a fascinating
example of a fad,

00:53:06.810 --> 00:53:08.740
and a very influential one.

00:53:08.740 --> 00:53:10.870
Al Gore once thought
about applying it

00:53:10.870 --> 00:53:12.832
to the United States
government, which may not

00:53:12.832 --> 00:53:15.260
have been a bad idea, I guess.

00:53:15.260 --> 00:53:17.650
And it was based on
the idea that you

00:53:17.650 --> 00:53:24.160
could take a particular
process or a company

00:53:24.160 --> 00:53:27.990
or any organization, break it
down into its component parts,

00:53:27.990 --> 00:53:30.820
analyze each individually,
relate them to each other,

00:53:30.820 --> 00:53:34.440
and then them together again
into some more efficient form.

00:53:34.440 --> 00:53:39.860
And it sort of swept the
board in the mid 1990s

00:53:39.860 --> 00:53:42.381
because it was seen to be
a way of taking advantage

00:53:42.381 --> 00:53:45.005
of the digital revolution, which
was part of what's Boyd's OODA

00:53:45.005 --> 00:53:53.370
loop did, and gave you the
possibility of being much more

00:53:53.370 --> 00:53:56.150
efficient, creating more
shareholder value, and so on.

00:53:56.150 --> 00:54:00.450
The problem was it soon became
associated with redundancy

00:54:00.450 --> 00:54:05.230
because in order to demonstrate
where the change had happened,

00:54:05.230 --> 00:54:08.750
as often as not those who'd
been through the process

00:54:08.750 --> 00:54:12.560
said and we've lost these
people who've been let go,

00:54:12.560 --> 00:54:15.580
whatever the euphemism is.

00:54:15.580 --> 00:54:19.050
And the consequence of
that is that as soon

00:54:19.050 --> 00:54:20.990
as firm started talking
about business process

00:54:20.990 --> 00:54:24.700
re-engineering, the workforce
got a little anxious

00:54:24.700 --> 00:54:27.480
and resistance set in.

00:54:27.480 --> 00:54:30.180
And then like so many
of these fads, which

00:54:30.180 --> 00:54:33.060
had been over hyped, once people
started looking at the claimed

00:54:33.060 --> 00:54:36.090
successes, they found other
reasons or the successes

00:54:36.090 --> 00:54:38.120
didn't last and so
on and so forth.

00:54:38.120 --> 00:54:43.830
And often it had some quite
good ideas in it got lost.

00:54:43.830 --> 00:54:46.020
And also one of the
problems with it

00:54:46.020 --> 00:54:49.890
was the narrative around it.

00:54:49.890 --> 00:54:54.910
So when you had the proponents
of this saying management

00:54:54.910 --> 00:55:00.960
has joined the dangerous
professions, help the wounded

00:55:00.960 --> 00:55:03.690
but should the
stragglers, and so on,

00:55:03.690 --> 00:55:06.360
that sort of macho language
with which it was spoken about

00:55:06.360 --> 00:55:08.630
was also part of the resistance.

00:55:08.630 --> 00:55:13.770
So I think a lot of this
is a warning against hype.

00:55:13.770 --> 00:55:16.710
I mean, any organization
needs to look at its process.

00:55:16.710 --> 00:55:20.510
And some strategies need
a change in process.

00:55:20.510 --> 00:55:22.830
Some processes lead to
a change in strategy.

00:55:22.830 --> 00:55:24.930
But it's all these
things, this belief

00:55:24.930 --> 00:55:27.050
that you've got the
winning formula that

00:55:27.050 --> 00:55:28.870
will be the key to
everything that's

00:55:28.870 --> 00:55:30.887
often the cause of trouble.

00:55:30.887 --> 00:55:31.970
BORIS: Thank you everyone.

00:55:31.970 --> 00:55:36.580
Please join me in thanking
Sir Lawrence Freedman.

00:55:36.580 --> 00:55:41.466
[APPLAUSE]

